{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Article topics can be classified through their references, citations, full text, or metadata (Boyack et al., 2011; Klavans & Boyack, 2017).",
    "Of these, full text in machine readable format is not widely available for academic journals and both direct citations (Wang & Waltman, 2016) and co-citations are unavailable for most recently published articles.",
    "Thus, the two possible options were bibliographic coupling and article textual metadata.",
    "The latter was chosen as a practical step because the article references needed for bibliographic coupling cannot be downloaded from the Scopus Applications Programming Interface (API), and there are too many Scopus articles from 2022 (2.9 million) to manually download all records from the web interface, given the 2000 records per query (with references) download limit.",
    "In addition, text similarity methods are relatively transparent in that the main terms causing high similarity scores can be identified."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Article topics can be classified through their references, citations, full text, or metadata (Boyack et al., 2011; Klavans & Boyack, 2017).",
    "Of these, full text in machine readable format is not widely available for academic journals and both direct citations (Wang & Waltman, 2016) and co-citations are unavailable for most recently published articles."
  ]
